				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Slow isn't a requirement in any group I've ever been in. It's nice, but not required. Slows are also resisted an awful lot, even beastlords slows which has been suggested are resisted less then shaman or enchanters, lol. I don't hunt in tier 2 or 3 planes normally but honestly that's as much by choice as design. I don't put 6 to 10 hours a day into EQ for raiding so I don't try and challange gods. I figure that's fair. 
<br />
 
<br />
 Near as I can tell you're mad that mobs hit too hard and too fast for you to solo. Because of this you complain and offer suggestions to nerf other class's ability to attempt to do so. Though to be honest I'm not sure how effective bards, shamans beastlords or enchanters are at soloing up there. Bards besides pissing off alot of people tend to get summoned or simple run out of running room shamans while they have nice slows and some good dots their pet isn't of the cailber to tank one of the planar mobs and they also get summoned. Beastlords whom was the original focus of this thread while they have a good slow and a decent pet/heal without actually meleeing don't put out enough dps to effectively solo mobs with planar lvl hp. Was talking to a guy last night trying it, he said it took like 30 minutes a mob if he wanted to be safely. Lastly there are enchanters, well with dire charm I imagine if there is a class who can solo well it's them, however considering the excessive trials and tribulations they have to go through for a majority of their careers I don't see a problem with there being a payoff at the end. Generalities aside in my personal opinion I don't think anyone should be able to solo, let alone do it safely in the planes.  No, btw I didn't comment on kiting class's, figure we're a pet class and tried to keep it somewhere near that focus.
<br />

<br />
Oh, and on that idea of breaking slow, which make no mistake is exactly what you're suggesting. Out of curiousity since you're wanting to cripple a lvl 65 spell to be as effective as a lvl 14 one what is your intent on every other slow spell in the shaman and enchanter line/s? Beastlords and enchanters only get 4 slow spells each (unless I miscounted the chanter ones) shamans get 5 magic based and 2 diseased based slows. That's not including necromancers with their undead only slows and any procs or other class's like bards. Oh, and in this can I assume that you will make slow spells impossible to be completely resisted, which is often exactly what happens when people cast them, oh and reduce the aggro they cause as well. Oh, and I assume you would allow for multiple castings of the slow spells to override each other if one's percentage comes up higher then the prior one even if they are the same spell. 
<br />
All also get a number of haste spells, perhaps you want to make those random as well eh? 
<br />

<br />
 Each class brings their talants to a group. Some overlap but each class is designed with the attempt (not always successful) so that each can offer something to a group and no one is clearly better then another comprable class. The basic formula suggests a tank, healer, slower and damage dealer with 2 slots open for whatever's avialable. Shamans and enchanters offensive spells aren't particulary effective nor are shamans great healers however thier ability to slow assures that they have a place in groups, least in theory. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Someone commented about dd's sometimes being resisted but bsts healing being a sure thing. That is true, however in my mind that's a reflection of the roles of the 2 class's. Beastlords are defensive in design, yes that still means they should have what little offensive spells they have, however their great strength their pet heals are a defensive ability and defense is normally easier then offense which is what mages are. It's why clerics will be taken to places at levels that tanks and casters would get laughed at. Heals don't get resisted /shrugs.
<br />

<br />

<br />
 Edit: Just an idea, but why not ask for a summoned/planar mob slow line? Necromancers get 2 slow spells one at 20 one at 39. In my mind getting an equilivent slow spell at 49 as the necro lvl 39 spell that effected planar/summoned mobs would give you what you want. Possible adding another one at 65 that's less resisted, to make getting to 65 more appealing. I'm not going to say I think it's balanced, but I wouldn't complain if it got added.<br />_________________<br />Member of the guild Wings of Valor on the E-marr server.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
